author:1657768025=
diff:1657768025:1657756503:=262,264c262,264%0a%3c When you get all your stats to 18, then the stat cap becomes 25.  No skills will require more than 20 in 2 different stats and a lvl 20 character.  So at endgame everyone will have an opportunity to be pro, regardless of character creation rolls (barring extremly uncommon bad rolls).%0a%3c %0a%3c The reason I combined introvert and extravert in the same class is mainly because they have all the same cognitive functions in relatively similar order.  So you can easily choose your stat rolls at creation and allocations throughthe levels to make either type in the same class.  Also some people tend to be more introverted in real life and extraverted online or vice versa.  I think the reason for this is that games are inherently an escape, so you tend to rather use your secondary function in games as a form of release from real life where you always lead with your primary.  Since a game doesn't really matter in real life, you tend to fall back on your secondary and more relaxing and impulsive function because stress doesn't force you into your primary.  This is mainly for casuals.  Once you become a hardcore gamer, you tend to use your real life personality because the stakes are higher and you feel like you must take the game seriously.  The classes in this game work perfectly for both casuals and hardcore players, and can adapt over time via your point allocation as you level.  Both hardcore and casual players of the same personality type are the same class, but will allocate stat points likely differently.%0a---%0a> When you get all your stats to 18, then the stat cap becomes 25.  No skills will require more than 20 in 2 different stats and a lvl 20 character.  So at endgame everyone will have an opportunity to be good, regardless of character creation rolls (barring extremly uncommon bad rolls).%0a> %0a> The reason I combined introvert and extravert in the same class is mainly because they have all the same cognitive 